individual data and group means plot

#ggplot(heart) plots Normalized.Signal as a function of Genotype
#geom_point plots individual observations on this plot
#geom_errorbar points to my group means df heart_sum1 and the bounds of the mean+/- standard error bar
#the successive geom_point plots the mean; specify color so it does not conflict with the color call in the first geom_point

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(heart,aes(x = Genotype,
                 y = Normalized.Signal))+
  geom_point(aes(color = Name,
                 shape = Organ),
             alpha = 2.0,
             size = 2,
             position = position_jitterdodge())+
    geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA,
               alpha = 0.1)+
  stat_summary(fun= mean, geom="point",
               shape=3, size=5,stroke = 1,color="red", fill="black")+
  geom_errorbar(data = heart_sum1,
                aes(ymin = Normalized.Signal-sd,
                    ymax = Normalized.Signal+sd,
                    width = 0.2))+
  geom_point(data = heart_sum1,
             size = 0.4,
             alpha = 1.0,
             color = "red")+
  xlab("Naa10 genotype")+
  ylab("NAA10 signal normalized to
       REVERT total protein stain")+
  theme_bw(base_size = 12, base_family = "Helvetica")

Unpaired t-test of NAA10 signal grouped by Genotype

Null hypothesis: there is no mean difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 male genotypes

Alternative: there is a difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 male genotypes

t.test(heart$Normalized.Signal~heart$Genotype,
       paired = F,
       var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  heart$Normalized.Signal by heart$Genotype
## t = -4.6832, df = 7.473, p-value = 0.001892
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Naa10 -/Y and group Naa10 +/Y is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -37741.03 -12630.28
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Naa10 -/Y mean in group Naa10 +/Y 
##                2948.205               28133.859

paired t-test of NAA10 signal between replicates of individual animals

Null hypothesis: there is no difference in NAA10 signal of individual livers on replicate blots Alternative hypothesis: there is a difference in NAA10 signal of individual livers on replicate blots

According to the paired t-test (t = -0.18, df = 5, p = 0.87), I fail to reject the null hypothesis. Ie, when I analyze the normalized NAA10 signal in technical replicates of each biological replicate, there is no difference in the NAA10 signal between technical replicates.
